<article>
    <h1>Men on friends, love, the state of the world</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200723/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-23"><time>2020-07-23</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | MUSIC</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ben&#xAD;son Ang Life&#xAD;style Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent bang@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Ten Chi­nese music works re­cently re­leased by male mu­si­cians ex­plore di­verse topics such as cam­pus crushes, lone­li­ness, mar­riage and the state of the world.</p>
    <p>1</p>
    <p>R&B/RAP</p>
    <p>GRAD­U­A­TION BROTHER</p>
    <p>Lin Meng-chen</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Spo­tify and other on­line music plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/3fxzHNg</p>
    <p>Boy­ish Tai­wanese new­comer Lin Meng-chen is off to a promis­ing start with his first sin­gle, Grad­u­a­tion Brother, a groovy song about puppy love.</p>
    <p>The 20-year-old run­ner-up in Tai­wanese re­al­ity singing com­pe­ti­tion Jun­gle Voice raps and sings with a youth­ful con­fi­dence, show­ing nat­u­ral like­abil­ity and lots of po­ten­tial.</p>
    <p>Watch this space.</p>
    <p>2</p>
    <p>R&B/HIP-HOP</p>
    <p>AWAKEN THE WORLD</p>
    <p>WayV</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Ap­ple Music and other on­line music plat­forms</p>
    <p>With their pol­ished de­meanour and fu­tur­is­tic syn­th­pop-in­flu­enced songs, the cool fac­tor of seven-mem­ber Chi­nese boy group WayV is un­de­ni­able.</p>
    <p>On their first stu­dio al­bum Awaken The World, sev­eral tracks such as Un­break­able and Bad Alive will get you on your feet.</p>
    <p>3</p>
    <p>POP</p>
    <p>UNBELONGIN­G</p>
    <p>Chen Li­nong</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Spo­tify and other on­line music plat­forms</p>
    <p>Chen Li­nong (above), a former mem­ber of Chi­nese boy band Nine Per­cent, shows his sen­si­tive side in his debut solo al­bum, Unbelongin­g.</p>
    <p>That ap­pears to be his strength, as he pop­u­lates the work with in­tro­spec­tive songs such as This Is How I Feel You and Lost In You.</p>
    <p>The tender duet Un­sure, with Tai­wanese singer Lala Hsu, raises philo­soph­i­cal ques­tions about life and hu­man con­nec­tion.</p>
    <p>4</p>
    <p>POP</p>
    <p>MU­SEUM OF TEARS</p>
    <p>Zheng Xing</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Ap­ple Music and other on­line music plat­forms</p>
    <p>Chi­nese singer-song­writer Zheng Xing’s (above) first al­bum, When I Leave Taipei (2017), scored him nom­i­na­tions for Best New Artist, Best Man­darin Al­bum and Al­bum of the Year at the Golden Melody Awards.</p>
    <p>In his sec­ond al­bum, Mu­seum Of Tears, he con­tin­ues to im­press with his sooth­ing voice, po­etic lyrics and well-con­structed works.</p>
    <p>In the ti­tle track, he re­mem­bers the sig­nif­i­cance of tears shed over hurt, re­gret or be­trayal.</p>
    <p>5</p>
    <p>ELEC­TRONIC/RAP</p>
    <p>KING</p>
    <p>Alfred Sim, fea­tur­ing Ian Fang</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Spo­tify and other on­line music plat­forms</p>
    <p>This fu­sion work by Sin­ga­porean singer Alfred Sim (above left) evokes grandiose images of a mighty warrior in the heat of battle.</p>
    <p>Fea­tur­ing erhu and guzheng sounds, thump­ing elec­tronic beats and an en­er­getic rap by Me­di­a­corp ac­tor Ian Fang (above right), King is a song with plenty of fight.</p>
    <p>6</p>
    <p>POP</p>
    <p>TIPTOE LOVE</p>
    <p>Huang Jinglun</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Ap­ple Music and other on­line music plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/32xMUlJ</p>
    <p>Eleven years after his sec­ond al­bum OK Man, Sin­ga­porean singer Huang Jinglun has re­leased a cover of tender bal­lad Tiptoe Love. The song, about wait­ing for love, was orig­i­nally per­formed by Tai­wanese fe­male singer Hung Pei-yu in 2011.</p>
    <p>It is a good choice as his high-pitched voice – of­ten com­pared with Tai­wanese bal­lad prince Jeff Chang’s – per­fectly con­veys the sense of an­tic­i­pa­tion and un­cer­tainty in the song, show­ing that men also have insecuriti­es.</p>
    <p>7</p>
    <p>POP I MISS YOU SO Nat Wu Hear it on: KKBox, Ap­ple Music and other on­line music plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/30eqz9H</p>
    <p>In re­cent years, Sin­ga­porean singer-song­writer Nat Wu (above) has been steadily gain­ing fans with his charm­ing per­son­al­ity and charis­matic live per­for­mances.</p>
    <p>Dur­ing the Covid-19 pan­demic, he con­tin­ues singing live reg­u­larly from his home via Face­book.</p>
    <p>His lat­est sin­gle, I Miss You So, shows sup­port for fam­i­lies and friends amid the cri­sis: “I want to go out for a walk/wher­ever you wanna go.”</p>
    <p>Its mov­ing music video fea­tures footage of him per­form­ing in places such as the Es­planade, Ma­rina Bay and *Scape.</p>
    <p>8</p>
    <p>ROCK</p>
    <p>DROWN­ING IN POI­SON</p>
    <p>Rub­berBand</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Spo­tify and other on­line music plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/2B0eA7a</p>
    <p>In the midst of the coro­n­avirus pan­demic, Hong Kong quar­tet Rub­berBand (above) have re­leased Drown­ing In Poi­son, an angsty Can­tonese song which presents a gloomy, cyn­i­cal per­spec­tive of the state of the world.</p>
    <p>The lyric video fea­tures an im­age in­spired by a fa­mous oil paint­ing, The Anatomy Les­son Of Dr Ni­co­laes Tulp (1632) by Dutch painter Rem­brandt, but twisted to ex­press the song’s dark themes.</p>
    <p>9</p>
    <p>POP</p>
    <p>FAIRY TALES</p>
    <p>Hacken Lee</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Spo­tify and other on­line music plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/3fzU10k</p>
    <p>Vet­eran Hong Kong singer Hacken Lee’s lat­est Can­tonese song is a sober­ing, pes­simistic look at adult re­la­tion­ships, one far re­moved from the ro­man­tic fan­tasies in fairy tales.</p>
    <p>Fairy Tales’ music video traces the course of a mar­riage, from its hope­ful start to dis­ap­point­ing end. The re­la­tion­ship is blighted by quar­rels, com­plaints and other com­plex­i­ties.</p>
    <p>10</p>
    <p>POP</p>
    <p>MISS U</p>
    <p>Richie Jen</p>
    <p>Hear it on: KKBox, Spo­tify and other on­line music plat­forms Watch it on: bit.ly/38XBmt3</p>
    <p>If you are think­ing of old friends you have lost con­tact with, Miss U by Tai­wanese ac­tor-singer Richie Jen is the per­fect song to lis­ten to.</p>
    <p>Nos­tal­gic and bit­ter­sweet, the folksy num­ber looks back at a child­hood con­nec­tion, sim­pler times and small plea­sures, and car­ries the hope that the peo­ple who are now out of your life are do­ing well.</p>

